    <h2>1. TCP Client-Server Application (String Length Counter)</h2>
    <h3>Flow of Communication</h3>
    <div class="flow-step"><strong>1. Server Bind & Listen:</strong> The server establishes a <code>ServerSocket</code> on port 5000 and executes a blocking <code>accept()</code> method, waiting passively for clients.</div>
    <div class="flow-step"><strong>2. Client Connection:</strong> The client instantiates a standard <code>Socket</code> using the host IP and port. This initiates the underlying TCP 3-way handshake (SYN, SYN-ACK, ACK).</div>
    <div class="flow-step"><strong>3. Stream Setup:</strong> Upon handshake validation, both endpoints extract <code>InputStream</code> and <code>OutputStream</code> objects, wrapped inside <code>BufferedReader</code> and <code>PrintWriter</code> layers.</div>
    <div class="flow-step"><strong>4. Payload Transmission:</strong> The client writes text into its output stream. The server breaks its blocking state on <code>readLine()</code> and captures the character payload string.</div>
    <div class="flow-step"><strong>5. Logic Execution & Echo:</strong> The server calculates the character length using <code>string.length()</code>, sends the integer back, and both elements safely teardown connection contexts via <code>close()</code>.</div>

    <h3>TCPServer.java</h3>
<pre>
import java.io.*;
import java.net.*;

public class TCPServer {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int port = 5000;
        try (ServerSocket serverSocket = new ServerSocket(port)) {
            System.out.println("Server listening on port " + port + "...");
            while (true) {
                try (Socket clientSocket = serverSocket.accept();
                     BufferedReader reader = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(clientSocket.getInputStream()));
                     PrintWriter writer = new PrintWriter(clientSocket.getOutputStream(), true)) {
                    
                    String inputClientString = reader.readLine();
                    if (inputClientString != null) {
                        writer.println(inputClientString.length());
                    }
                }
            }
        } catch (IOException e) { e.printStackTrace(); }
    }
}
</pre>

