    <h2>2. JavaMail API & Protocols</h2>
    <p>The <strong>JavaMail API</strong> is an abstract, platform-independent framework designed to build robust messaging and email clients within Java applications. It isolates developers from dealing with low-level socket programming and raw RFC network string standards.</p>
    <h3>Core Core Network Protocols Supported:</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>SMTP (Simple Mail Transfer Protocol):</strong> Outgoing mail transportation standard protocol used to push messages from clients to servers or route them between mail nodes. (Port 25 / 587).</li>
        <li><strong>POP3 (Post Office Protocol v3):</strong> Single-device store-and-forward download protocol. It fetches emails from remote servers onto local mail storage and, by default, deletes them off the server. (Port 110 / 995).</li>
        <li><strong>IMAP (Internet Message Access Protocol):</strong> Advanced synchronized multi-device retrieval engine. It mirrors state representations natively on the mail server infrastructure directly, enabling remote updates and structural sorting. (Port 143 / 993).</li>
    </ul>

