    <h2>3. Remote Method Invocation (RMI)</h2>
    <p><strong>RMI (Remote Method Invocation)</strong> allows an object residing in one JVM to execute method calls on an object running in a completely different JVM across a network connection layer seamlessly.</p>
    
    <h3>RMI Layered Architecture Diagram</h3>
    <div class="diagram-placeholder">
        [Client Application Workspace]<br>
        ⬇ (Invokes Abstract Local Method)<br>
        <strong>[Stub Layer Proxy]</strong> ──(Marshals/Serializes Parameters Over Wire)──➔ <strong>[Remote Ref Layer]</strong><br>
        ⬇<br>
        [Low-Level Transport Layer (TCP/JRMP Wire Standard)]<br>
        ⬇<br>
        <strong>[Skeleton Layer Proxy]</strong> ──(Unmarshals/Deserializes Raw Objects)──➔ [Server Object Implementation]
    </div>

    <h3>RMI Sum Interface & Implementation</h3>
<pre>
// Calculator.java
import java.rmi.*;
public interface Calculator extends Remote {
    public int computeSum(int num1, int num2) throws RemoteException;
}

// CalculatorImpl.java
import java.rmi.server.*;
import java.rmi.*;
public class CalculatorImpl extends UnicastRemoteObject implements Calculator {
    public CalculatorImpl() throws RemoteException { super(); }
    public int computeSum(int num1, int num2) { return num1 + num2; }
}
</pre>

