    <h2>8. JDBC Driver Paradigms & SQL Injection Mitigation</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Type-1 Driver (JDBC-ODBC Bridge):</strong> Translates operations to native ODBC configurations. Requires client machine configurations. (Obsolete).</li>
        <li><strong>Type-2 Driver (Native-API Driver):</strong> Conversions route through database-specific local binary client dependencies. Performance scales, but damages portability.</li>
        <li><strong>Type-3 Driver (Network Protocol Middleware):</strong> Maps methods to a middleware server setup before execution on the target database engine.</li>
        <li><strong>Type-4 Driver (Thin Pure-Java Driver):</strong> Compiles statements directly into database-specific network protocol streams. High execution tracking and maximum performance.</li>
    </ul>
    <h3>SQL Injection Vulnerability Resolution via PreparedStatement</h3>
    <p>SQL Injection arises when unvalidated text concatenation mutates core query compilation structures. <code>PreparedStatement</code> prevents this security vulnerability by compiling the SQL template structural execution syntax beforehand using positional parameter arguments (<code>?</code> placeholders). Values passed later are processed strictly as literal values rather than executable commands.</p>

