    <h2>13. Static vs. Dynamic Web Apps & Servlets</h2>
    <p><strong>Static Web Applications</strong> deliver flat, pre-compiled file assets directly from file storage to the client browser without any logical modification. <strong>Dynamic Web Applications</strong> evaluate request arguments at runtime to build unique contextual view documents dynamically using databases and calculation layers.</p>
    <p>A <strong>Servlet</strong> acts as a server-side controller that catches incoming requests, performs processing logic, reads from data tables, and dynamically generates the response stream returned to the user.</p>

    <!-- Q14 -->
    <h2>14. Detailed Java Servlet Lifecycle Architectural Phases</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Initialization Phase (<code>init()</code> Method):</strong> Executed exactly once by the container engine context when mounting the servlet memory framework. Best suited for resource configurations like database connections.</li>
        <li><strong>Request Processing Phase (<code>service()</code> Method):</strong> Fired concurrently across distinct routing worker threads for every inbound request. Inspects the HTTP action verb (GET/POST) to route traffic down to <code>doGet()</code> or <code>doPost()</code> methods.</li>
        <li><strong>Destruction Phase (<code>destroy()</code> Method):</strong> Triggered exactly once by the container engine configuration prior to garbage collection cleanup. Closes active resource attachments.</li>
    </ul>

    <!-- Q15 -->
    <h2>15. The `doGet()` vs. `doPost()` Request Framework Management</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong><code>doGet()</code>:</strong> Appends parameters to the terminal end of the plaintext URL path context query lines. Constrained by maximum text limits and unsafe for private data parameters.</li>
        <li><strong><code>doPost()</code>:</strong> Streams data inside the underlying HTTP transport body layer structure. Supports large file buffers and keeps data hidden from the URL bar.</li>
    </ul>

